SIMPLE: lilt
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lilt
<hw>Lilt</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧lt)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Norw.
<ets>lilla</ets>, <ets>lirla</ets>, to sing in a high tone.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To do anything with animation and quickness, as to
skip, fly, or hop.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Wordsworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To sing cheerfully.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lilt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lilt
<hw>Lilt</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To utter with spirit, animation, or
gayety; to sing with spirit and liveliness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A classic lecture, rich in sentiment,⟦br⟧
With scraps of thundrous epic <qex>lilted</qex> out⟦br⟧
By violet-hooded doctors.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lilt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lilt
<hw>Lilt</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Animated, brisk motion;
spirited rhythm; sprightliness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The movement, the <qex>lilt</qex>, and the subtle charm of the
verse.</q> <rj><qau>F. Harrison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A lively song or dance; a cheerful tune.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The housewife went about her work, or spun at her wheel, with a
<qex>lilt</qex> upon her lips.</q> <rj><qau>J. C. Shairp.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>lilting</ent>⟦br⟧
